04399nam a22005415i 9780231558297DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315582977 a10.7312/kott210142doi  a(DE-B1597)679652  a(OCoLC)1416744854  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aD843b.K68 2024eb 7aHIS0371002bisacsh04a909.82/5223/eng/202309251 aKott, Sandrine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA World More Equal :bAn Internationalist Perspective on the Cold War /cSandrine Kott. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in International and Global History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Acronyms -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Two Parts of Europe During the Postwar Period -- t2. The Emergence of a “Second World”: Center and Periphery -- t3. Internationalisms During the Cold War -- t4. The Europe of Convergences -- t5. The Third World and the New International Economic Order -- t6. From Internationalisms to Globalism: The Slow Agony of the Cold War -- tConclusion: Beyond the Cold War -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe post–World War II period is typically seen as a time of stark division, an epochal global conflict between the United States and the Soviet Union. But beneath the surface, the postwar era witnessed a striking degree of international cooperation. The United Nations and its agencies, as well as regional organizations, international nongovernmental organizations, and private foundations brought together actors from conflicting worlds, fostering international collaboration across the geopolitical and ideological divisions of the Cold War.Diving into the archives of these organizations and associations, Sandrine Kott provides a new account of the Cold War that foregrounds the rise of internationalism as both an ideology and a practice. She examines cooperation across boundaries in international spaces, emphasizing the role of midsized powers, including Eastern European and neutral countries. Kott highlights how the need to address global inequities became a central concern, as officials and experts argued that economic inequality imperiled the creation of a lasting peace. International organizations gave newly decolonized and “Third World” countries a platform to challenge the global distribution of power and wealth, and they encouraged transnational cooperation in causes such as human rights and women’s rights. Assessing the failure to achieve a new international economic order in the 1970s, Kott adds new perspective on the rise of neoliberalism. A truly global study of the Cold War through the lens of international organizations, A World More Equal also shows why the internationalism of this era offers resources for addressing social and global inequalities today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCold War. 0aWorld politicsy1945-1989. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century / Cold War.2bisacsh1 aGharibian, Arby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074968740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kott2101440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231558297423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231558297/original  a978-3-11-074968-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles